04250nam a22006495i 9780292796492DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212001txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927964927 a10.7560/7122702doi  a(DE-B1597)587414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHQ536.15.T4bC37 2001eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.85/09764/090342221 aCarroll, Mark M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomesteads Ungovernable :bFamilies, Sex, Race, and the Law in Frontier Texas, 1823-1860 /cMark M. Carroll. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tONE. Ardent Adventurers and Borderland Beauties -- tTWO. Eros and Dominion -- tTHREE. Intimacy and Subjugation -- tFOUR. Turbulent Prairie Homes -- tFIVE. Slip-knot Marriages and Patchwork Nests -- tSIX. Iniquitous Partners -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliographical Commentary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen he settled in Mexican Texas in 1832 and began courting Anna Raguet, Sam Houston had been separated from his Tennessee wife Eliza Allen for three years, while having already married and divorced his Cherokee wife Tiana and at least two other Indian "wives" during the interval. Houston's political enemies derided these marital irregularities, but in fact Houston's legal and extralegal marriages hardly set him apart from many other Texas men at a time when illicit and unstable unions were common in the yet-to-be-formed Lone Star State. In this book, Mark Carroll draws on legal and social history to trace the evolution of sexual, family, and racial-caste relations in the most turbulent polity on the southern frontier during the antebellum period (1823-1860). He finds that the marriages of settlers in Texas were typically born of economic necessity and that, with few white women available, Anglo men frequently partnered with Native American, Tejano, and black women. While identifying a multicultural array of gender roles that combined with law and frontier disorder to destabilize the marriages of homesteaders, he also reveals how harsh living conditions, land policies, and property rules prompted settling spouses to cooperate for survival and mutual economic gain. Of equal importance, he reveals how evolving Texas law reinforced the substantial autonomy of Anglo women and provided them material rewards, even as it ensured that cross-racial sexual relationships and their reproductive consequences comported with slavery and a regime that dispossessed and subordinated free blacks, Native Americans, and Tejanos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDomestic relationszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aFamilieszTexasy19th century. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezTexasy19th century. 0aSex rolezTexasxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71227040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796492/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK